   The decor was kind of boring and unstylish, and like all Loving Huts
   they had songs from the Supreme Master and her followers playing (I
   think there was  TV playing them, but I canâ€™t remember).  I personally
   find this distracting and a little strange, since Iâ€™m not a follower.
   But hey, itâ€™s their restaurant and they serve some damn good food, so I
   canâ€™t complain too much.  The staff were incredibly friendly (as
   always), and my waitress spoke English!  I of course canâ€™t guarantee
   that  all servers do, but if youâ€™re nervous about ordering in Japanese
   they may be able to help.

   P1030244

   Overall, I definitely recommend visiting this Loving Hut location.  It
   has some delicious food for really reasonable prices, and with itâ€™s
   central location and take-out dishes, itâ€™s ideal for visiting tourists.

The Great Tokyo Vegan Donut Quest

   January 7, 2015January 7, 2015 / therrymonk13 / Leave a comment

   When my friends came to visit me in Tokyo last July, we set out on an
   epic quest, a quest for an treasure so rare and delightful that at
   first we doubted itâ€™s very existence:  the vegan Tokyo donut.  Sadly,
   as our primary destination was the fabled La Terre, our adventure was
   wrought with sorrowâ€¦

   1. La Terreâ€™s Donuts â€“ NOT quite Vegan!

   Weâ€™d heard that La Terre, located right across from Tâ€™s Tantan in Tokyo
   Station, had a pretty big assortment of vegan donuts.  So, we
   hightailed it from Shinjuku Station, desperate for a bit of these
   amazing donuts.

   P1050824

   Not everything was milk free, but surprisingly, 6 of their donuts
   listed only soy and wheat as allergens!  We were ecstatic, and picked
   out our favorites. However, at the last second I started to wonderâ€¦
   what about honey?

   Unfortunately, after asking the incredibly friendly and helpful staff
   about the ingredients, they confirmed that ALL of the donuts â€“
   including the rumored vegan donuts â€“ contained honey. ğŸ˜¦  So,
   unfortunately, unless youâ€™re a honey-eating-vegan, these donuts arenâ€™t
   for you.  Itâ€™s such a shame, they were SO close, and they looked so
   delicious!

   My friends had to head back home, so unfortunately, they were unable to
   complete the mission.  However, I was not to be deterredâ€¦
   La Terre's Mashed Soybeans Donut - Contains honey!

   La Terreâ€™s Mashed Soybeans Donut â€“ Contains honey!
   La Terre's Soymilk Cream Donuts - contain honey!

   La Terreâ€™s Soymilk Cream Donuts â€“ contain honey!

   2. Doughnut Plant NYC â€œBakery Donutâ€ (Â¥260 Each) â€“ sometimes VEGAN!

   Thereâ€™s been a lot of confusion surrounding Doughnut Plant NYCâ€™s
   vegan-ness, so Iâ€™d like to set the record straight.  Doughnut Plant NYC
   has branches in the US as well as in Japan, and they use different
   recipes. Doughnut Plant NYC (US) has no vegan options.  Doughnut Plant
   NYC (Japan) used to have many vegan options, which were sold at Eat
   More Greens in Azabu-Juban and at Doughnut Plant NYCâ€™s various Tokyo
   locations.  However, in the last few years theyâ€™ve cut back on these
   options.  The donuts served at Eat More Greens are no longer vegan.
   However, if you go to one of Doughnut Plant NYCâ€™s shops, you may be
   able to find a vegan donut.  They seem to only carry 1 or 2
   soymilk-based donuts at a time, but when I visited in July they were
   available!

   They revolve their flavors seasonally, so check their menu before you
   go to see what you can eat.  Underneath each menu item, they list the
   allergens. For example, the Banana Pecan donut that listed currently
   has an allergy disclaimer that says: â€œâ€»ç‰¹å®šåŸææ–™ï¼šå°éº¦ ã€å¤§è±†ã€ãƒãƒŠãƒŠâ€.  No milk!
   Keep an eye out for ä¹³ (milk) and åµ (egg) in the allergen section. If
   neither is listed, itâ€™s probably vegan!

   When I visited their Shinjuku Location (just inside the Kabukicho Exit
   of Shinjuku Station, up a short flight of stairs), they had a vegan
   Pistachio Donut.  I asked when I ordered if it contained honey, and the
   lovely sales person checked the ingredients for me â€“ no honey!  I was
   ecstatic after my failure at La Terre, and happily devoured it.

   P1050925

   P1050923

   Iâ€™ve had vegan cake donuts at Whole Foods and Peppleâ€™s Donuts in San
   Francisco, but this was my first time in years Iâ€™d gotten to try
   bakery-style fluffy donuts (the only other place Iâ€™ve seen them is
   Voodoo Donuts in Portland).  Sadly, it wasnâ€™t jaw-droppingly incredible
   â€“ I would have preferred more glaze â€“ but it was still pretty good and
   satisfied my donut craving.
   Doughnut Plant NYC - Pistachio Donut

   Doughnut Plant NYC â€“ Pistachio Donut

   P1050931

   3. Mana Burgerâ€™s â€œMana Malasadaâ€ ( Â¥330 each) â€“ VEGAN!

   Mana Burger is a Hawaiian fast food restaurant located in Tama-Plaza,
   Kanagawa. Itâ€™s not technically in Tokyo, but itâ€™s close enough to make
   the list (just 24 minutes from Shibuya Station).  When I visited here I
   wasnâ€™t expecting to find donuts, but when I saw them on the menu I knew
   I had to have one!  Iâ€™d never had a Malasada before, so I was really
   excited to try it.  And I can now safely say that the Malasada is quite
   possibly my favorite cinnamon-rolled member of the international donut
   family.  It was increeeedible!  Definitely not to be missed!
   Mana Malasada - Â¥330

   Mana Malasada â€“ Â¥330

   4. Pure Cafeâ€™s â€œHomemade Cream Donutsâ€ (Â¥420 each) â€“ VEGAN!

   Sadly, there is one Tokyo donut that I desperately wanted but failed to
   obtain â€“ Pure Cafeâ€™s absurdly deliciously-looking cream-filled donuts.
    They seem to release them only in the morning and only on certain days
   of the week (last I saw it was Wednesdays), and since I had to work
   Wednesday morning, I never made it there in time for one.  Seriously,
   though, look at these things (photos from the Pure Cafe Facebook).  How
   could they NOT be amazing?
   1545091_657613664282247_2070643521_n

